<Author>A TripAdvisor Member
<Content>Simply Superb Having booked my 25yr old son into the Conde Duque for fortnightly business visits since February, I joined him for a 4 day break from 5 June 2006. My son has expensive tastes, is not a traditionalist and always likes to be 'cutting edge'; as his PA, I have booked him into many hotels around Europe and when in Madrid this is his favourite hotel. Normally he favours modern Intercontinental type hotels but due to the quality, value for money, location and atmosphere the Conde Duque meets all his expectations admirably. I had known the efficiency and helpfulness of the Commercial Dept through emails exchanged with Paloma (Commercial Director) and was looking forward to meeting her and her staff. I was not disappointed - the genuine warmth, courtesy and helpfulness was so refreshing.The hotel is elegant and exudes that essential Spanish traditionalist air without being old-fashioned - an oasis of calm coolness after the heat and activity out and about Madrid. Everything about the hotel is just right, facilities, cleanliness, comfort and superb staff.The location is superb being set in a delightful leafy Plaza where families met and children safely played - in the evening after an excellent dinner, at the adjoining restaurant, it was a delight to amble around the Plaza feeling completely safe and without risk of roudy drunks disturbing the environment. At the Conde Duque you are based in an attractive 'local' area close to the centre of the city - although there are some excellent hotels in the Sol and Plaza Mayor areas they suffer the disadvantage of being too 'touristy'. For my money I'd rather enjoy feeling like a 'local' and avoiding the noise and problems in the tourist haunts.Whether travelling from the Airport or getting around the city, the Metro is 'the way' to travel. The San Bernardo station (Line 4) is approximately 400yds from the hotel, just around the corner. A metro ride from the airport to hotel costs Euro1 per person and involves one simple change of line (Line 8 travelling 2 stops to Mar de Cristal, to connect with Line 4 and then 16 stops to San Bernardo) - it couldn't be easier or cheaper and the trains are immaculate. Getting any metro train costs the same Euro1 however many (internal) line changes you make to your exit destination - why bother taking more expensive taxi rides!I loved Madrid and the Conde Duque played a very large part in my happy memories of my visit - I almost didn't want to right this review as it's one of those 'gems' of a place you want to keep all to yourself ! - however it was through reading earlier TA reviews of the Conde Duque that led us to enjoy it's delights in the first place. Try it - you'll enjoy it too. 
